The effect of seed germination and growth were accessed in the film degraded soil using black gram plant for a week. The shoot and root length were examined and calculated to analyse the impacts of films degraded soil on plant growth of black gram (Fig. 8
                        ). The shoot and root length of black gram were displayed in Table 2
                        . An average of 10 seeds was subjected to seeding for germination. It was monitored for the above said period and seed germination, shoot and root lengths were calculated. The shoot length of the reference plant is 11.28 cm whereas the shoot length of films degraded soil such as chitosan/PVP, NCDs/chitosan/PVP, orange peel/ chitosan/PVP, NCDs/orange peel/chitosan/PVP were 11.31, 11.35, 12.05, 12.11 cm which is showed an increment in length by 0.03, 0.07, 0.77, 0.83 cm respectively. The root length of reference plant is 4.88 cm whereas root length of films degraded soil such as chitosan/PVP, NCDs/chitosan/PVP, orange peel/ chitosan/PVP, NCDs/orange peel/chitosan/PVP were 4.94, 5.28, 6.31, 5.15 cm which is showed an increment in length by 0.06, 0.4, 1.43, 0.27 cm respectively. Similarly, the average leaves length of reference is 3 cm whereas the average leaves length of films degraded soil such as chitosan/PVP, NCDs/chitosan/PVP, orange peel/ chitosan/PVP, NCDs/orange peel/chitosan/PVP were 3.65, 3.9, 3.8, 3.75 cm which showed an increment in length by 0.65, 0.9, 0.8, 0.75 cm respectively. It is clearly observed that film degraded soil exhibits a higher shoot, root length, and leaves length when compared to reference plant due to the presence of chitosan, NCDs, and orange peel extract where chitosan is a bio-fertilizer and allows the sustained release of fertilizer [38], NCDs help to provide sufficient moisture content through the hydrophilic oxygen containing hydroxyl and carboxyl groups on the surface which aids easy uptake of water to the seeds [39], and orange peel extract is a potential source of nitrogen and micronutrients and provides adequate nutrients to the soil and regulate the pH of the soil [40] as a result of an enhanced root, shoot and leaves length. Moreover, the secondary root formation is significantly higher for all the film degraded soil. Overall, the film degraded soil shows the positive impact on seed germination and growth of the black gram plant.
